Section 1:
1 L.D. 1093
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 AGRICULTURE, CONSERVATION AND FORESTRY
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 715, L.D. 1093, “An Act to Direct the
10 Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry, Bureau of Parks and Lands to
11 Prevent the Use of the Term "State Park" by Nonstate Parks”
12 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'An Act Regarding Day Use Passes That May Be Used at Any State Park or Historic
14 Site'
15 Amend the bill by inserting after the title and before the enacting clause the following:
16 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
17 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
18 Whereas, the season for visitation to state parks and historic sites will begin soon,
19 and this legislation needs to take effect before the expiration of the 90-day period to allow
20 the change made by this legislation to take effect as soon as possible; and
21 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
22 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
23 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
24 therefore,'
25 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
26 following:
27 'Sec. 1. 12 MRSA §1819-C is enacted to read:
28 §1819-C. Day use pass for state park or historic site
29 The director shall issue, for a fee, a day use pass that can be used at a state park or
30 historic site. The pass entitles the holder to admission to all state parks and historic sites
31 under the jurisdiction of the bureau.
32 This section does not apply to a state park or historic site that is subject to a lease on
33 the effective date of this section and managed by an entity other than the bureau. This
34 paragraph is repealed January 1, 2030.
Page 1 - 132LR1997(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 715, L.D. 1093
1 Sec. 2. State parks and historic sites; existing leases. For a state park or historic
2 site that is subject to a lease on the effective date of this Act, the Department of Agriculture,
3 Conservation and Forestry, Bureau of Parks and Lands shall require such a park or historic
4 site to allow admittance to the holder of a day use pass pursuant to the Maine Revised
5 Statutes, Title 12, section 1819-C at the expiration of the lease term of any such lease.'
6 Amend the bill by adding before the summary the following:
7 'Emergency clause. In view of the emergency cited in the preamble, this legislation
8 takes effect when approved.'
9 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
10 number to read consecutively.
11 SUMMARY
1122 It is currently policy of the Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry,
1133 Bureau of Parks and Lands to issue, for a fee, a day use pass that can be used at any state
1144 park or historic site in the State, with some exceptions.
1155 This amendment replaces the bill and changes the title. The amendment requires the
1166 Director of the Bureau of Parks and Lands to issue, for a fee, a day use pass that can be
1177 used at any state park or historic site under the jurisdiction of the bureau except for any
1188 state park or historic site that is subject to an existing lease and managed by an entity other
1199 than the bureau. This exception is repealed January 1, 2030. The amendment further
2200 provides that for any state park or historic site subject to an existing lease, the bureau must
2211 require such a park or historic site to allow admittance to the holder of a day use pass that
2222 can be used at any state park or historic site at the expiration of the lease term. The
2233 amendment also adds an emergency preamble and emergency clause to the bill.
2244 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
2255 (See attached)
Page 2 - 132LR1997(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
